<HEADLINE>
FT  15 FEB 94 / Spitalfields building plan given start date
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The first stage of the planned redevelopment of the former Spitalfields
fruit and vegetable market, to the east of the City of London, is set to
start within a year.
Spitalfields Holdings, which owns the 13-acre site, expects to agree a deal
in the next six weeks with a developer to fund and build up to 160 homes on
part of the site.
Spitalfields Holdings is jointly owned by LET, the property developer, and
Costain and Balfour Beatty, the construction companies.
The long-awaited initial development is likely to comprise town houses and
flats at the northern end of the site. The housing will be aimed at the
upper end of the market, although much will depend on detailed planning
consent.
The decision to press ahead with the housing component of the scheme
reflects the relatively strong state of the housing market in central
London, compared with the office market. With the exception of a few schemes
in the centre of the City, there is unlikely to be demand for large-scale
development of new offices in the City for some years.
Sales of new houses in Great Britain are estimated to have risen by between
10 per cent and 15 per cent last year, excluding one-off sales to housing
associations, compared with a 5 per cent rise in sales of all types of
homes.
The outline planning consent consists of 900,000 sq ft of offices and
300,000 sq ft of residential and retail units.
The total project is planned to be developed in phases as market conditions
improve. In its latest report, Costain put the scheduled completion date for
the project at 2001. A temporary market now occupies part of the site.
The severe recession in the City office market in the early 1990s has cast
doubt on the value of the scheme. Costain's 1992 accounts wrote down the
cost of the interest capitalised on the scheme at Pounds 25.7m, putting its
book value at Pounds 45m, with a further Pounds 18m premium to be paid to
the Corporation of London over three years.
</TEXT>
