<HEADLINE>
FT  15 FEB 94 / Post-graduates 'underused' by industry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW FISHER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Industry is being held back in the fast-changing areas of science and
technology by its low employment of post-graduate engineers and scientists,
a report said yesterday.
The National Institute of Economic and Social Research compared British and
German companies and said that British employers were concerned that
post-graduates were too specialised and less likely than first-degree
graduates to acquire commercial and practical skills.
UK companies' limited use of post-graduates was also a result of 'the
relatively slow growth, by international standards, in British manufacturing
investment in research and development'. The institute also warned that
under-employment of highly qualified personnel by many British companies put
them at a disadvantage against foreign rivals.
It pointed out, however, that a strength of the British higher education
system - in contrast to Germany - was its production of young first-degree
graduates whose abilities (although not academic standards) were often the
equal of older German graduates.
The institute looked at the chemicals and engineering sectors. In
engineering, it identified close links between the German industry's greater
employment of technical post-graduates and its superior performance in
product and process innovations, with benefits for the country's export
competitiveness.
The German advantage, it said, is particularly marked in the high-speed
machinery sector but less so in chemicals.
High-level skills and industrial competitiveness: post- graduate engineers
and scientists in Britain and Germany. NIESR, 2 Dean Trench Street, Smith
Square, London SW1. Pounds 9.
</TEXT>
