<HEADLINE>
FT  15 FEB 94 / Slow increase in sales points to 'patchy' recovery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GRAHAM BOWLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Business in shops, stores and supermarkets increased at the slowest rate for
a year last month, according to the Confederation of British Industry.
The CBI's monthly survey of distributive trades shows small retailers as
performing badly. While large multiple stores saw their sales grow
significantly in January, smaller shops reported a decline.
Larger retailers however were more optimistic. The survey shows that of
stores with more than one outlet, the balance of those reporting an increase
in sales over those reporting falls was 32 per cent. This contrasted with a
net balance of 16 per cent of retailers with a single outlet reporting
declines.
Mr Nigel Whittaker, chairman of the CBI's distributive trades panel, said
the figures highlighted the patchy nature of the recovery.
'Although only four sectors report slight falls in volumes, most sectors
still say that sales are below average for the time of year,' he said.
The survey comes ahead of official figures for January's retail sales, to be
published tomorrow. Before today's survey these were expected to show an
improvement, largely due to New Year sales, after a decline in December.
The findings of the survey will come as a disappointment after recent
trading statements which painted a more optimistic picture of the retail
sector.
Mr Whittaker said: 'Looking ahead, prospects for retailers have changed
little from December. The increase in sales in February is expected to be
only slightly higher than the growth recorded in January. Expectations are
the weakest since last May, pointing to continued modest growth in
high-street demand.'
The survey shows that there were increases in sales across most sectors,
with booksellers, stationers, grocers, footwear and leather retailers among
those showing the best improvement.
But specialist food shops, confectioners and hardware, china and DIY
retailers all reported that volumes are down on a year ago and all other
sectors reported similar slow growth rates.
Growth in wholesalers' sales volumes increased in January. They remain above
average for the time of year. However, the survey reports that both
wholesalers' and retailers' stock levels are still too high in relation to
expected demand.
Motor traders had a better start to the year, growing at the highest rate
since August 1988, and business is considered to be well above average for
the time of year.
</TEXT>
