<HEADLINE>
FT  15 FEB 94 / Bad press worries Scottish Enterprise
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Concern was expressed yesterday by Scottish Enterprise, the economic
development network for Scotland outside the Highlands, that bad publicity
would discourage businessmen from serving on the boards of local enterprise
companies.
The local enterprise companies have recently been under scrutiny from the
Scottish media, with attention concentrated on potential conflicts of
interest between directors' business interests and those of the Lecs.
Mr Crawford Beveridge, chief executive of Scottish Enterprise, told the
opening session of an inquiry by the Scottish select committee of the House
of Commons that not one case of conflict of interest involving a director of
a Lec had been found.
Scottish Enterprise has been criticised by some observers for spending too
much on marketing itself.
However Mr Beveridge said marketing this year would cost Pounds 10m,
compared with Pounds 13m spent in the last year of the Scottish Development
Agency and the Training Agency, the predecessors of Scottish Enterprise.
