<HEADLINE>
FT  15 FEB 94 / World Trade News: US weighs use of sanctions bludgeon -
Nancy Dunne assesses Washington's reaction to an 'unacceptable' Japanese
surplus
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Japan is now so strong and wealthy that its massive trade surplus is 'simply
no longer acceptable,' US President Bill Clinton said yesterday.
After the failure of the US-Japan summit to agree on a plan to reduce the
surplus, Mr Clinton said he was reviewing all options and ruling out
nothing.
Ms Laura D'Andrea Tyson, chairman of the Council of Economic Advisers, said
US officials had embarked on 'a series of meetings and a series of actions.'
But she said there had been no action as yet. 'We should not be talking
about trade war now.'
In fact, there may be no sanctions for months. Sanctions announcements are
likely and, if the administration's pressure is successful, negotiations may
follow.
However, the administration is united on one point: any pacts must be
watertight to produce results.
The administration's credibility is at stake - in Congress, with the US
public and with China, which is being told that the US needs progress on
human rights by June if China's Most Favoured Nation trade status is to be
renewed.
Officials yesterday acknowledged that the president was considering an
executive order that would resurrect the now expired Super 301 provision of
the trade law.
This would provide a domestically legal basis for a broad range of trade
complaints, followed by investigations, negotiations, and deadlines for
sanctions.
However, Mr Clinton added that he was considering 'some (options) that have
not been widely discussed that may offer great promise.'
There has been some suggestion, for example, that the administration may
gamble on a complaint to the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade alleging
that Japan's invisible market barriers 'nullify and impair' its trade
liberalisation pledges. This might assuage critics who say US unilateral
action is destructive to the world trading system.
The administration could also attack Japan's keiretsu system of interlocking
companies by bringing an anti-trust case against Japanese subsidiaries in
the US. The Federal Trade Commission has already begun an anti-trust
investigation.
Meanwhile, Mr Mickey Kantor, the US trade representative, has asked the US
Customs Service for data to be used in developing a sanctions list. It is
thought this could speed the retaliatory process if senior administration
officials decide a quick response to the summit failure is necessary.
The most likely area for sanctions is cellular telephones, with today set as
the deadline for a review of the cellular telephone pact with Japan. But
another candidate is the semiconductor deal, which was supposed to help
foreign manufacturers get at least 20 per cent of the Japanese market. The
target was hit in the fourth quarter last year - sales, slowed by the
Japanese recession, have been sinking ever since.
Last year, the Clinton administration followed its predecessors in setting
aside numerous trade complaints for the sake of getting the Uruguay Round
completed. In the same period, access to Japan's public works market was
agreed and its rice market was pried open.
However, a broad menu of options for sanctions remains: candidates can be
gleaned from the most recent of the National Trade Estimates reports, issued
yearly by the US trade representative. The most recent NTE devotes 27 pages
to Japan - more than any other country and 10 more than the EC - and there
is vast scope for trouble between the economic superpowers.
Japan's government procurement practices have long been a target of US
complaint. Sanctions in that area - in response to government discrimination
against US computers and supercomputers - would be likely to hit Japanese
companies that bid for US contracts.
Another pact the US could find actionable is the US-Japan Wood Products
Agreement signed in 1990. The NTE noted 'significant strides' made towards
reducing market access barriers, but concluded that 'satisfactory market
access ultimately hinges on the implementation of agreed-upon tariff
reductions in the Uruguay Round.'
Zero for zero tariff cuts were not agreed, and the failure convinced US
officials the Hosokawa government was less than serious about its
deregulation efforts. 'That alone would have brought down housing costs by
50 per cent  .. but they absolutely refused to do it,' said one senior US
official.
Japan's insurance market - one of four sectors in the failed talks - is
another nominee for sanctions. Japan has decided to begin insurance
deregulation in the areas of nursing home care, medical insurance, and
personal and travel accident - the only sectors where foreign companies have
access.
</TEXT>
<XX>
