<HEADLINE>
FT  15 FEB 94 / World Trade News: Motorola may spark showdown
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Foreign Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The first shots in a US-Japan trade showdown could be heard today over a
complaint by Motorola that the Japanese have not complied with a cellular
telephone agreement to open their market.
The US company, which is the world's leading manufacturer of cellular
telephones, has struggled for years to make inroads into the Japanese
market. A review of the pact was launched early this year, with today set as
the deadline by Mr Mickey Kantor, US trade representative.
President Bill Clinton yesterday said sanctions against Japanese cellular
telephones imported by the US were under consideration. He said the review
deadline today was 'quite concidental', but 'illustrative' of the
difficulties facing foreign companies in Japan. Mr Kantor could launch
retaliation proceedings, followed eventually by sanctions. That process
could take months.
In 1992, US telecommunication equipment sales to Japan accounted for about 4
per cent of the market and were dropping, from Dollars 699m (Pounds 477m) in
1991 to about Dollars 555m.
</TEXT>
