<HEADLINE>
FT  15 FEB 94 / Canadian dollar dives to 8-year low
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Canadian dollar dived to its lowest level in eight years yesterday,
despite persistent intervention by the Bank of Canada.
The currency was partly a victim of the strength of the Japanese yen and
European currencies against the US dollar. But traders said the weakness was
exacerbated by uncertainty over the new Liberal government's policies.
The Canadian dollar closed at 73.92 US cents yesterday, having touched a low
of 73.75 US cents during the day. It had closed at 74.43 on Friday.
Mr Paul Martin, the finance minister, will table his first budget on
February 22. It is expected to include spending cuts and a broadened tax
base, but Mr Martin has indicated the deficit is unlikely to fall below
CDollars 39bn-CDollars 40bn (Pounds 19.5bn-Pounds 20bn) in the next fiscal
year, compared with about CDollars 45bn this year.
Currency markets have also been unnerved by indications that the government
is eager to push domestic interest rates down further. With the long decline
in US rates now ended, such a move would narrow the traditional spread
between US and Canadian rates.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>CAZ  Canada.
</CN>
<XX>
