<HEADLINE>
FT  15 FEB 94 / Major backs Russia's G7 application
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Major last night became the first western leader to give public
backing to Russia's demand for full representation in the political
deliberations of the Group of Seven western industrial nations.
As the British prime minister arrived in Moscow last night for talks with
President Boris Yeltsin, British officials said Moscow should be granted
'full and equal' treatment during political discussions at annual G7
summits. For the past two years it has had only observer status.
Mr Yeltsin called for a place at the G7 table in a letter to leaders last
month. Officials travelling with Mr Major said the UK prime minister had the
tacit support of President Bill Clinton and Chancellor Helmut Kohl. But
Japan, still in dispute with Russia over sovereignty of the Kurile islands,
was likely to oppose the move. France might also be less than enthusiastic.
They accepted also there was no question at present of admitting Russia to
the G7's economic deliberations. Other members are Italy and Canada.
Mr Major believes strongly that with Mr Yeltsin under threat from both the
old Communist guard and the Russian nationalist right, the west cannot
afford to treat Russia as a 'second class citizen'. He wants Mr Yeltsin's
application accepted in time for the president to play a full part in this
summer's Naples summit.
Officials denied any direct link with Mr Major's attempt to persuade Mr
Yeltsin to give tacit support to last week's Nato ultimatum to the Bosnian
Serbs. But they stressed that if the west expected Russia to continue to
play a constructive role in deliberations over Bosnia in the UN Security
Council, it had to offer Mr Yeltsin real influence in the wider
deliberations of the G7.
</TEXT>
