<HEADLINE>
FT  15 FEB 94 / Governor named for central bank
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MURRAY BROWN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ISTANBUL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Yaman Toruner, a 45-year-old former bank official and currently the
chairman of the Istanbul stock exchange, has been appointed as Turkey's new
central bank governor following the resignation of Mr Bulent Gultekin last
month, writes John Murray Brown in Istanbul. Mr Toruner is the third
governor to serve under Turkey's prime minister Tansu Ciller since she took
office last June. Both previous incumbents resigned over policy differences
with the prime minister.
Mr Toruner's main task will be to restore confidence in the lira after last
month's 12 per cent devaluation. His chief tool will be interest rates.
However with rates on government securities already at 125 per cent for
one-year paper, the government is trying to restrain further increases as a
way to reduce its budget costs.
