<HEADLINE>
FT  15 FEB 94 / Yen driven up by trade deadlock: Japanese share prices hit
by fears of lost export sales
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM DAWKINS and PHILIP GAWITH
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Nervous financial markets yesterday pushed the yen to its highest level in
five months and drove leading Japanese stocks sharply lower in response to
the weekend failure of the US and Japan to reach a trade agreement.
The stronger yen reflects investor fears that the Clinton administration is
determined to talk up the Japanese currency as a way of curbing a Dollars
50bn (Pounds 34bn) trade deficit by making Japanese exports more expensive.
The US administration said yesterday that it would not be hasty in
considering its response to the failed talks. President Bill Clinton said:
'We are reviewing all our options. We haven't ruled anything out.'
Asked whether US sanctions could lead to retaliation and a trade war, he
said: 'It could be, but I think they (the Japanese) would have to think long
and hard about it.'
The Nikkei share average fell nearly 650 points to about 18,800 in early
trading this morning after falling 531.45 in the previous session amid fears
that Japanese groups would lose export sales as a result of a strong yen.
In Tokyo early today the yen was trading at Y102.175 against the dollar
after rising sharply yesterday in New York where it briefly touched Y101
before closing at Y102.2. In London, it finished at Y104.1, against its
Friday close in New York of Y107.2.
Japan's leaders said they would take steps before the July summit of the
Group of Seven leading industrialised nations to deal with the deficit. Mr
Morihiro Hosokawa, prime minister, told his coalition partners that the
situation 'must be improved' and that the continuing surplus with the US was
'not favourable'. The government and private sector must both make efforts
to reduce the surplus, he said.
The prime minister received support from Mr Michio Watanabe, a faction
leader in the opposition Liberal Democratic party, who warned that Japan
risked a trade war with the US unless it worked out market-opening measures.
The US administration made clear, however, that any move to reopen talks
should come from Japan. Mr Mickey Kantor, US trade representative, said:
'They understand exactly what the framework means. They understand the need
to open up their markets.' He said US officials would meet all week to
formulate a response to 'the failure of the Japanese government to live up
to their obligations'.
The renewed rise in the Japanese currency provoked concern from the Bank of
Japan, which said it would take steps in co-operation with other
industrialised countries if the currency speculation continued.
Currency analysts also warned against the dangers of the yen strengthening
too far. Mr Neil MacKinnon, chief economist at Citibank in London, noted
that a 10 per cent appreciation in the yen would result in a 0.5 per cent
fall in Japanese gross domestic product growth. 'Even from the US point of
view, there must be a recognition that a Japanese economy that is expanding
is preferable to one that is flat on its back,' said Mr MacKinnon.
Mr Mark Cliffe of Nomura Research Institute in London said the strong yen
would undermine confidence further, squeeze profits and threaten more
labour-shedding.
US weighs use of sanctions bludgeon, Page 5
Japan coalition allies consider party merger, Page 6
Lex, Page 18
Currencies, Page 33
World stocks, Page 39
</TEXT>
