<HEADLINE>
FT  14 FEB 94 / Viacom pulls ahead in Paramount bid stakes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Viacom, the US cable television group, last night looked the clear favourite
to win the Dollars 10bn battle for control of Paramount Communications,
which formally comes to a close tonight.
QVC Network, the rival bidder in the five-month struggle, said yesterday
that it would not raise its own bid further.
Since investors last week expressed a clear preference for Viacom's offer,
it seemed likely that Sumner Redstone's cable television group would come
out in front.
It remained unclear, though, whether Viacom would be able to muster enough
support to declare an outright victory by tonight.
If it does not speak for at least 50.1 per cent of Paramount's shares, then
the formal bidding process for the group will end and the battle will
collapse into a free-for-all.
QVC's statement yesterday that it would not offer more for Paramount came
after a succession of hints last week that it might change the terms of its
bid.
'We said we would not bid above the prudent value for the company, and we
haven't,' it said.
QVC added, though, that it believed it would be a better owner of Paramount
than Viacom, and it continued to question some aspects of Viacom's bid.
Viacom's B shares dropped by 4 per cent in New York on Friday, signalling a
clear belief that it will come out on top in the five-month battle.
Investors fear that whichever company is the victor will be weighed down
financially by the takeover.
The price of Viacom's B shares fell Dollars 1 1/8 to Dollars 31 5/8 on
Friday in a trading session which was shortened by an early stock market
close due to bad weather. The shares have now almost halved in value since
last September, when Sumner Redstone's cable TV group first bid for
Paramount.
While both offers for Paramount are worth around Dollars 10bn, Viacom has
won Wall Street's support with a higher cash component in its bid, along
with guarantees for Paramount shareholders should its own share price fall
in the year after a takeover.
At five months and two days, the Paramount bidding war is now just two days
short of the record five-month, four-day takeover of computer company NCR in
1991, the longest takeover fight in recent Wall Street history.
</TEXT>
