<HEADLINE>
FT  14 FEB 94 / Observer: A Syron voice at the Amex
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Richard Syron has his work cut out at the American Stock Exchange, where he
took over as head at the end of last week. A distant third to the New York
Stock Exchange and Nasdaq markets, the Amex looks increasingly superfluous
in a world of automated trading. Syron, 50, admits the Amex has had an
unhappy few years: 'I don't think we've done as well as we need to do.'
The former head of the Federal Reserve in Boston has no detailed plans on
how to reverse matters, only a belief that the sort of auction market run by
the Amex serves investors better than the dealer markets which are
increasingly prominent in the US. Unfortunately, the Securities and Exchange
Commission has steadfastly refused to favour auction markets.
In five years at the Boston Fed Syron built a solid reputation as a tough,
astute operator. Fixing the Amex will need all his energy and political
skills - and then some.
</TEXT>
