<HEADLINE>
FT  14 FEB 94 / Votes speed communication unions merger
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Delegates from the two biggest communications unions voted decisively to
merge yesterday.
The votes, taken at separate delegates conferences in Bournemouth, marked
the first and most important step in the merger process between the Union of
Communication Workers and and the National Communications Union which is
expected to create a single group by December.
Delegates from the 175,000-strong UCW and the 126,000-member NCU were being
asked to back a legally binding instrument of amalgamation. The UCW voted
overwhelmingly to support the amalgamation and the NCU was two-to-one in
favour.
Discussions on a combined rulebook went less smoothly but union leaders said
they expected their executives to reach an acceptable compromise on rules to
allow the merger to be voted upon at the annual conferences of the unions in
May and June.
Conference decisions in favour of the merger will then be put to the full
memberships for a final endorsement.
The two union general secretaries - Mr Alan Johnson of the UCW and Mr Tony
Young of the NCU - said their ability to defend members' jobs would be
strengthened if everybody was in the same union.
Both unions face continuing membership losses because of the rundown in
jobs. The merger, which will create a union of some 310,000 members, is seen
as a way of strengthening the industrial power of workers in the Post Office
and British Telecommunications and also as a way of opening up new
recruitment areas in Mercury and cable television.
Mr Young said the proposal was 'not a takeover of one union by another'. but
'a genuine partnership'. The two general secretaries will work in tandem
until 1998.
The proposed merger timetable requires a postal ballot of the members of
both unions to agree on a name for the new body to take place over March and
April. While several names have been suggested, the most likely choice is
the Communications Workers Union.
One possible obstacle could emerge tomorrow when the result of the NCU
general secretary election is to be announced. Mr Young has faced a
difficult struggle against Mr Bill Fry, a leftwing candidate, who wants the
union to adopt a more militant strategy.
</TEXT>
