<HEADLINE>
FT  14 FEB 94 / Surrey councils set out reform plans
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Surrey district councils have announced plans to split the county into
either five or six unitary authorities as part of the English local
government review.
The move follows the call by Mr John Gummer, environment secretary, for
local authorities to negotiate mergers which should then be presented to the
Local Government Commission. However, Surrey county council has not yet
decided on a formal policy towards the review, and at present leans towards
retaining the two-tier status quo.
Under the district councils' proposals, Woking, Surrey Heath and Runnymede
would merge to form one authority, and there would also be mergers of
Guildford and Waverley; Elmbridge and Spelthorne; Tandridge, Reigate and
Banstead, and of Mole Valley and Epsom and Ewell.
