<HEADLINE>
FT  14 FEB 94 / Fines for soft drugs may leap to Pounds 2,500
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Michael Howard, home secretary, will decide this week whether to impose
the first increase for 17 years in penalties for possession of a broad range
of illegal drugs, Kevin Brown writes.
He is considering proposals to raise the maximum fine for possession of
class B drugs from Pounds 500 to Pounds 2,500.
The main drugs affected would be cannabis, barbiturates and amphetamines.
There are no plans to increase penalties for possession of class A drugs
such as heroin and cocaine.
Home office officials say that a five-fold increase in penalties is needed
to take account of inflation and to bring fines into line with tougher
penalties for other offences.
Higher penalties would also signal that the government does not intend to
legalise soft drugs such as cannabis. Officials said there were no plans to
reduce the number of cautions for drug possession, which account for about
half of all cases investigated.
However, ministers are understood to be concerned that penalty increases
could worsen the backlog of court cases if it led to a rise in non-payment
of fines. If Mr Howard decides to go ahead, the government will table an
amendment to the criminal justice bill, currently passing through
parliament.
Organisations representing people who deal with drug users questioned the
logic of the move. The charity Release said increasing the maximum fine
would have no positive effect.
The Police Federation said the present maximum fine was rarely used.
Mr Tony Blair, Labour's home affairs spokesman, said the government should
concentrate on tackling the growing problem of hard drugs.
</TEXT>
