</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  14 FEB 94 / Procedural war set to escalate
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A row over the workings of a Commons committee is threatening to trigger a
damaging escalation of Labour's procedural war against the government.
Sir Terence Higgins, a senior Conservative backbencher, is trying to defuse
the argument, which has arisen over the Labour leadership's refusal to allow
its MPs on the Commons trade and industry committee to go on a planned trip
to South Africa.
Matters may come to a head on Wednesday when Tory MPs who form a majority on
the committee are threatening to force a vote of no confidence in Mr Richard
Caborn, its Labour chairman. Such a move would be expected to provoke Labour
to retaliate.
Sir Terence, a former Treasury minister, has been handed his troubleshooting
role by virtue of his chairmanship of the liaison committee, the body which
co-ordinates the work of the select committees.
Sir Terence said last week that the liaison committee was strongly of the
view that it would be wrong for any dispute between the political parties to
interfere with the work of the select committee system.
Mr Keith Hampson, a Conservative member of the trade and industry committee,
said Mr Caborn could have been removed last week but it had been decided to
give Labour time 'for common sense to prevail'. He added that the move was
not a personal attack on Mr Caborn.
Mr John Smith, the Labour leader, moved on Friday to scotch fears that
Labour's retaliation might take the form of removing its MPs from all
Commons committees. He said Labour would not take such a step because these
bodies were 'part of the work of parliament'.
Labour broke off all relations with the government in December in protest at
plans to curtail debate on bills implementing changes to statutory sick pay
and National Insurance contributions.
Under its protest even non-contentious legislation is being obstructed and
the practice of 'pairing' - whereby MPs can miss a vote by being linked to a
member in an opposing party who agrees to be absent as well  - has ended.
</TEXT>
