<HEADLINE>
FT  12 FEB 94 / Skiing in the deep freeze: Arnie Wilson finds the going
tough
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ARNIE WILSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The FT Round the World Skiing Expedition has crossed the ice curtain:
temperatures in Montana suddenly plunged and as the weatherman said: 'Nice
weather today if you're a husky.'
The Arctic conditions coincided with our faithful car - nicknamed Spud
because of its Idaho plates - giving up the ghost. The frozen Montana
wastelands are no place for a car with a flat battery.
'She's dead as a rock,' pronounced the mechanic hurriedly despatched from
Bozeman airport to Big Sky ski resort, where our own batteries had been
topped up with some exhilarating skiing.
A blue replica of Spud arrived on a low-loader, but my companion Lucy
Dicker, in the grip of a severe migraine, was scarcely aware that we had
changed cars.
This delay meant we arrived at Bridger Bowl just in time for me to ski its
famous ridge. This involves a steep, 25-minute climb, skis strapped to your
back, before trudging along a narrow ridge to tackle one of dozens of
challenging ungroomed chutes and gullies.
The migraine spared Lucy the ordeal of traversing into the apron - one
section is so steep, narrow and undulating that skiers are advised to grab a
tree known as 'Desperation Pine' if they slip. But like me, Lucy is
determined to ski every day of 1994 and so she struggled from the car to ski
Bridger's lower slopes in freezing conditions.
The following night we began a nightmarish nine-hour drive more than half
way across Wyoming in such freezing conditions that every time a huge truck
hurtled past it enveloped us in a cloud of carbon monoxide vapour.
You could win a skiing holiday for two in Courchevel or Verbier, or
runner-up prizes of malt whisky, by entering the competition which appeared
in last week's Weekend FT (copies available from the FT shop, tel: 071-873
3324).
The expedition's principal sponsors are: Avis; American Airlines; Air New
Zealand; Champagne Mercier; Clarins; Dynamic Skis; Fogg Travel Insurance;
Hewlett-Packard; Luhta; Salomon; Ski The Summit, Colorado; Snow + Rock.
</TEXT>
