<HEADLINE>
FT  12 FEB 94 / Property: How to beat the greedy gazumpers - Cadogan's Place
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GERALD CADOGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
With markets rising in London, gazumping could re-appear. Gazumping happens
when, after accepting an offer but before exchange of contracts, the vendor
rejects it to accept a higher offer.
The disappointed buyer then blames the vendor's agent although, often, it is
not the agent who is at fault.
Can anything be done to ensure vendors behave properly? Yes. Make your offer
conditional upon the vendor signing a 'lock-out' agreement.
This binds them not to accept any other offer for a stated period (although
it does not stop them showing other potential buyers around in case the deal
with you should fall through).
Buying agent Wilson &amp; Wilson, which has overseas clients who come a long way
to view properties, insists on these agreements. They promise that the buyer
will exchange contracts within 10 working days (two weeks) of receiving the
draft documentation. If that does not happen, the deal will almost certainly
lapse.
Meanwhile, inner London homes for sale include:
46 Clanricarde Gardens, W2. A superbly decorated flat near Notting Hill Gate
tube station. Pounds 195,000 for a 104-year lease. The agent is Egerton
(071-584 7020).
81 Peel Street, W8. A small house between Kensington High Street and Notting
Hill Gate for Pounds 290,000. Savills (071-221 1751).
38 Ringmer Avenue, SW6. A terrace house in Fulham with conservatory and
garden. Pounds 295,000. John D. Wood (071-731 4223).
9 The Mount, NW3. A Georgian house in the heart of Hampstead, with double
garage. Pounds 552,500. Hamptons (071-794 8222).
29 Percy Street, W1. A handsome, mid-Georgian house between Charlotte Street
and Tottenham Court Road. Pounds 650,000 (down from Pounds 700,000). William
H. Brown (071-636 2736) or Winkworth (071-240 3322).
17 Upper Grosvenor Street, W1. A large, first-floor Mayfair flat in a former
gentlemen's club with panelled drawing room. Pounds 675,000 for a 58-year
lease. Wetherell (071-493 6935).
29 Clabon Mews, SW1. A 1985 mews house with garage behind Cadogan Square.
Pounds 750,000 for 66-year lease. Egerton.
70 Eaton Square, Belgravia SW1. On the north end of the square's west side,
a first-floor flat with two splendid reception rooms and view down the
length of the square. Needs a complete overhaul. Pounds 1.35m for a new
20-year lease. Lassmans (071-499 3434).
27 Melbury Road, W14. A 1965, Georgian-style house with double garage and
off-street parking for three/four cars. Pounds 2.3m for 71-year lease. John
D. Wood (071-727 0705).
Last month, the river Lavant brought the worst flooding in 130 years to
Chichester, West Sussex. The river also runs through the nearby village of
East Lavant where, for around Pounds 500,000, Henry Adams &amp; Partners
(0243-533 377) is selling Paxtons, an 18th century brick and flint house in
two acres. Paxtons does not flood. It is on higher ground, and even the
cellars stayed dry during the deluge.
</TEXT>
<XX>
