<HEADLINE>
FT  12 FEB 94 / Food &amp; Drink: So, farewell Coonawarra claret - Jancis
Robinson explains a new wine treaty which will have far-reaching effects
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JANCIS ROBINSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Considering it produces well below 2 per cent of the world's wine, and is at
least 20 hours' flying time from most of the world's vineyards, Australia
wields an extraordinary amount of influence.
Most obviously, there is a strong Australian element in the training of
'flying winemakers', the swelling band of itinerant oenologists who are
shaping winemaking techniques in developing winelands all over the globe.
Of more long-term importance, perhaps, are the achievements of Australian
viticulturists in the world's vineyards, where they aim to flout the
conventional wisdom that quality and quantity are incompatible. But
signatures in Brussels and Canberra at the end of last month signalled an
important new area of Australian influence, as well as a new era for
Australian wine labelling.
Five years of intense negotiation have resulted in a two-part, 200-page
agreement by which Australia stops using Europe's cherished wine names -
champagne, burgundy, chablis, port, claret etc - at home as well as abroad,
in exchange for EU recognition of its winemaking techniques, its own
analyses, and EU renunciation of the right to use Australian geographical
wine names such as Coonawarra and Granite Belt.
There was a bit of a hiccup when the Portuguese objected to Port Stephens as
an Australian wine region but both negotiating teams are generally thrilled
with the detail of this treaty.
The turning point came when the Australians agreed to stop using the word
champagne (it maybe significant that some champagne houses have investments
in Australian wine). The Australians, on the other hand, clearly feel they
have stolen a march on other New World wine producers in terms of ease of
access of their wines.
They have won concessions on the low natural acidity and high mineral
content of some of their wines, on their naturally sweet wines which have
until now fallen foul of EU law, and on their distinctly un-European habit
of blending the produce of different regions.
But they are particularly smug about their practices which are embodied in
this, the EU's first bilateral wine trade agreement, representing an
important step in the international harmonisation of winemaking techniques.
It has already been used as a model for agreements with Bulgaria, Romania,
Hungary and New Zealand and is likely to provide a framework for
negotiations with such equally keen wine exporters as South Africa, Chile,
and Argentina.
The hardest country to bring into line will be the US, land of Gallo Hearty
Burgundy. It may be the world's fifth largest wine producer, but it has
nothing like Australia's commitment to exports, which now represent almost a
quarter of production worth ADollars 21m (roughly Pounds 10m), expected to
increase to ADollars 1bn by the turn of the century.
Some current Oz favourites chosen specifically to appeal to European
palates:
Goundrey Langton Mount Barker Chardonnay. 1993. Pounds 4.99. Asda. Still one
of the best bargains around, a relatively cool climate Chardonnay. The
Riesling 1991 is equally lively, although delightfully mature, and costs
Pounds 5.49 from Vin du Vin of Appledore, Kent (tel: 0233-83727), La
Vigneronne of London SW7 (071-589-6113), and Andrew Darwin of Kington,
Hereford (04544-230534).
Mt Langi Ghiran Riesling. 1993. Pounds 5.99. Oddbins and Winecellars of
London SW18 (081-871-2668). Fine; see also their Shiraz 1991 at Pounds 7.99.
Heritage Clare Valley Riesling. 1993. Pounds 6.49. Australian Wine Centre,
London WC2 (071-925-0751). Delightfully understated and subtle. Not a trace
of lime sherbet.
Prelude Chardonnay. 1991. Pounds 6.99. Domaine Direct of London WC1
(071-837-1142) A steal. Leeuwin Estate's second label and a wine that hints
broadly at the burgundian style of this top Western Australian Chardonnay at
Pounds 12.50.
Shaw &amp; Smith Sauvignon Blanc. 1993. Pounds 7.99. Oddbins, Adnams of
Southwold, Suffolk (0502-724222) and Winecellars. One of the most convincing
Sauvignons I have ever encountered.
Alkoomi Chardonnay. 1991. About Pounds 10. Castang of Looe, Cornwall
(0503-220359), Howard &amp; Hardman of Chipping Norton 0608-641850. Pure and
sinewy.
Heritage Cabernet Malbec. 1991. Pounds 6.99. Australian Wine Centre. Soft,
alluringly ripe and ready to drink.
Charles Melton Shiraz. 1992. Pounds 8.99. Winecellars. Rich, full,
immediate.
Rockford Dry Country Grenache. 1991. Pounds 9.75. Booths wine stores and
Adnams. Sweet, alcoholic, round, lightly oaked. A delicious gulp.
Henschke Abbott's Prayer Merlot/Cabernet. 1990. Pounds 11.99. Lay &amp; Wheeler
of Colchester (0206-764446). Subtle, and approachable.
Coldstream Hills Reserve Pinot Noir. 1992. Pounds 11.99. Oddbins The most
exciting Pinot yet to come out of Australia. Waitrose will have the
Cab/Merlot 1991 at Pounds 8.49.
Petaluma Coonawarra Red. 1988/1990. Pounds 9.99. Oddbins, Bottoms Up and
Wine Rack. As close as Coonawarra gets to claret.
Penley Estate Cabernet Sauvignon. 1990. Pounds 12.99. The Wine Treasury of
London SW6 (071-371-7131). Gorgeous, mellow, top quality.
</TEXT>
