<HEADLINE>
FT  12 FEB 94 / Finance and the Family: All eyes on Glaxo - The Week Ahead
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
On Monday Westminster Health Care, the nursing home group which was floated
in April, is expected to announce a sharp rise in profits at the interim
stage. For the six months to November, pre-tax profits are estimated at
Pounds 4.9m compared to Pounds 1.6m. The previous figure was stated after
interest of Pounds 2.7m, but the Pounds 64m proceeds from the float will
have cut that bill.
Hanson, the Anglo-American conglomerate, reports first-quarter results to
the end of December on Tuesday. There is a wide range of forecasts because
of the many uncertainties involved. The cost of the US coal strike, which
has now ended; the severity of the negative swing on interest charges; the
contribution from Quantum Chemical, acquired at the end of the last
financial year; and the effect of exchange rates. However, hopes are for a
modest underlying rise from last time's Pounds 216m, excluding Pounds 20m of
disposal profits.
Glaxo's half-year figures on Thursday kick off the UK's pharmaceuticals
sector results season. With SmithKline Beecham the following week, and
Wellcome and Zeneca in March, analysts will be examining the sector's
fortunes in an unfamiliar light: that of the yield. Until the early 1990s,
the drugs sector was the darling of the capital growth investors. But the
threat of cost-cutting in government healthcare budgets has stopped that in
its tracks.
This means that all eyes will turn first to Glaxo's proposed interim
dividend. Forecasts range from 8p to well over 9p, compared with last year's
7p. Even a rise at the lower end of the scale would be a powerful reminder
that a yield of almost 5 per cent compares favourably with a FT-SE 100
yielding less than 3.5 per cent.
Pre-tax profits of perhaps Pounds 970m, against Pounds 819m, are expected to
reflect falling interest income and tighter profit margins.
Alfred McAlpine on Thursday will become the first of the larger contractors
to announce annual results, for the year to October 31. The big question is
by how much Oliver Whitehead, the new chief executive, will write down the
company's assets following the departure of Graeme Odgers.
Profits should have benefited from the recovery in the UK housing and US
construction markets and are expected to be in the region of Pounds 6m
before write-downs. This compares with pre-tax profits Pounds 3.6m the
previous year.
Kleinwort Benson, the merchant bank, also reports annual profits for 1993 on
Thursday. Analysts are expecting a near doubling of profits to around Pounds
90m before a Pounds 10m profit on the sale of Sharps Pixley, the bullion
business sold to Deutsche Bank for Pounds 17.6m.
Wickes, the DIY and timber retailer, is expected on Thursday to announce a
strong increase in full-year profits to between Pounds 17m and Pounds 19m,
more than double last year's pre-exceptional figure of Pounds 7.8m. Analysts
are keen to hear whether Wickes is benefiting from the upturn in the housing
market, but are concerned about the impact of the recession on its
operations in continental Europe.
