<HEADLINE>
FT  12 FEB 94 / The Lex Column: Ladbroke/Burford
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Ladbroke's sale of a parcel of properties for Pounds 103m provides comfort
on two fronts. First, it highlights the new management's determination to
reduce its Pounds 1.3bn debt by selling off the more extreme parts of Mr
Cyril Stein's sprawling empire. Second, it hints that Ladbroke's properties
may indeed be worth what the accounts suggest, which has been a worry in the
market. That said, the deal has more significance in terms of sentiment than
substance for Ladbroke. The cash inflow is unlikely to prevent the company
from chopping its dividend. Ladbroke retains another Pounds 760m of
commercial property which may prove more difficult to shift.
It is easy to understand Burford's delight. The company has been quick off
the mark in securing a deal with one of the few sellers in the market.
Moreover, Burford is issuing new paper at a 27 per cent premium to its net
asset value to buy properties with an initial yield of 8.4 per cent. That
equation will immediately enhance asset values and earnings.
The package of properties contains a fair mix of investment grade assets and
dull office buildings. But it would be surprising if Burford failed to push
the yields higher with more active management. The expansion of Burford's
equity base should also enable it to gear up to buy riskier but more
rewarding secondary sites. That is where the investment money is now
heading.
</TEXT>
