<HEADLINE>
FT  12 FEB 94 / World Stock Markets: Japanese funds ask questions after
January rally - The latest economic stimulus package excludes stock market
support measures
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMIKO TERAZONO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The record Y15,250bn economic stimulus package announced by the government
earlier this week excluded stock market support measures, featured in the
previous three pump-priming packages presented over the past two years.
With the Nikkei average of 225 leading stocks safely over 19,000, government
officials are no longer losing sleep over the Tokyo stock market, which has
given the country's financial community a few nightmares since its plunge in
1990.
The leading force in the recent rise of Japanese share prices, however, has
been buying by foreigners. The Nikkei rose 16.1 per cent during January, as
overseas investors poured funds into Tokyo. US and European asset allocators
increased their weightings in Japan after sharp rises in south-east Asian
markets last year increased their downside risk.
A record Dollars 12bn in overseas funds was pumped into the Tokyo stock
market during January, and foreign fund managers piled into sectors such as
automobiles, electronics and steels.
The big question now is whether the Japanese institutional investors will
follow suit or the rally just be a 'foreigner' phenomenon. The argument for
domestic investors to join the buying is supported by low interest rates,
the bottoming out of the economy and corporate profits, and currency risk
acting as a deterrent to overseas investment.
Some economists are hopeful that corporate profits will improve this year
due to the sharp fall in depreciation. The predicted weakening of the yen is
also expected to support sales at leading exporters. However, the Nikkei 225
is now on a prospective p/e of 100, seriously worrying the fundamentalists.
Baring Securities advises an exposure of 42 per cent to the Japanese market
for a world fund. It is telling investors not to be frightened by the high
price/earnings ratios, saying that cheap stocks do not always rise and
stocks considered expensive do not necessarily fall. Foreign analysts hope
that the Y43,000bn held by Japanese investors in liquid deposits will start
flowing into the equity market, pushing up shares even further.
However, most Japanese investors remain cautious, arguing that underlying
economic fundamentals have not changed drastically, and that it is foreign
liquidity which has pushed share prices up. 'It's not as if corporate
earnings will recover immediately and buying by foreigners won't last
forever,' says a fund manager at Nippon Life, the country's largest life
assurer.
Domestic investors also faceno risk from lack of exposure to Japanese
stocks, since most of their holdings are in the Tokyo market.
Behind these big institutional concerns lies persistent gloom over the
country's economy. Nomura Research Institute, the research arm of Nomura
Securities, sees the real gross domestic product for the year ending March
1995 contracting by 0.4 per cent after shrinking 0.6 per cent in the current
year.
The effects of the economic stimulus package, including the income tax cut
on the corporate economy are expected to be minimal since, of the Y7,200bn
slated for public investment, almost 40 per cent is accounted for by prior
land acquisition for public work projects; and consumers, many of whom face
an increasing possibility of losing their jobs, are unlikely to spend the
extra income from their tax cuts.
Morgan Stanley in Tokyo points out that the impact of Y5,850bn in tax cuts
may be delayed significantly, for technical reasons. 'The delay in
announcing the stimulus package and the following political fiasco have
undermined the necessary consumer and business confidence that the package
was supposed to achieve,' says Ms Mineko Sasaki Smith, a Morgan Stanley
economist.
Meanwhile, corporate profits are expected to remain sluggish for the next
few years, due to the slow reduction in fixed labour costs. NRI forecasts a
22.4 per cent fall in its earnings of leading 400 companies for the current
year to March followed by a mere 2.9 per cent rebound in the next fiscal
year.
Another lingering concern for the investment community ahead of the March
year-end is the oversupply stemming from profit-taking, by corporations
improving their poor earnings through sales of their long term stock
portfolios. 'Corporate investors withheld their selling when the market was
going up, but will start unloading their shares when the momentum dies
down,' says one Japanese fund manager.
Growing arbitrage positions are also adding to Japanese institutional
worries. Long positions held against futures contracts totalled Y1,201bn
after the first week of February, the highest level since Y1,380bn in
October last year. The funds are afraid that a fall in futures prices could
trigger an unwinding.
For now, Japanese brokers are keeping their fingers crossed that foreign
buying support will last long enough to take the Nikkei safely through the
March book closing period. Mr Yasuo Ueki at Nikko Securities is betting on
the index closing the fiscal year at around 20,500.
</TEXT>
